sports court while you're on the go,
being able to check your

00:04:03.680 --> 00:04:05.700
email from your phone,
traveling to San Francisco,

00:04:05.700 --> 00:04:08.700
which would be nice to know where
a good restaurant to eat is.

00:04:08.700 --> 00:04:13.040
it is,
or even find directions to the hotel.

00:04:14.610 --> 00:04:18.590
So we started this little M-mode data
experiment way back in the mid-90s

00:04:18.600 --> 00:04:22.790
when we used to call it "pocket net."
And that was back when there was lots

00:04:22.790 --> 00:04:26.420
of hype around the "wireless internet."
I think those two words together

00:04:26.560 --> 00:04:31.060
back in the mid-90s were kind of an
oxymoron since there was really nothing

00:04:31.060 --> 00:04:37.690
internet about seeing a five-line
black-and-white LCD display trying to

00:04:37.780 --> 00:04:40.500
communicate what was on the internet.

00:04:40.610 --> 00:04:46.000
Running at 9.6 or 14.4 kbps wasn't
necessarily a very compelling experience.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:50.000
But it was a great opportunity for us to
get our feet wet and learn some lessons.

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:53.200
And some of the important things
that we picked up through this

00:04:53.290 --> 00:04:55.000
was obviously devices matter.

00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:59.000
You know, back then it was a big clunky
Mitsubishi or Sony Ericsson phone.

00:04:59.170 --> 00:05:01.140
And while it was pretty
advanced in its day,

00:05:01.140 --> 00:05:04.000
"I'm looking at the
wireless internet now,

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:07.460
I'm pulling out my antenna and waiting
for it to connect," was a rather

00:05:07.460 --> 00:05:10.480
underwhelming experience unless you
were a pretty patient individual.

00:05:10.500 --> 00:05:13.470
And also, the other thing we learned
there was content matters.

00:05:13.650 --> 00:05:16.620
Our approach then was a walled
garden approach where we said,

00:05:16.620 --> 00:05:19.550
"You can have unlimited access
to the wireless internet,

00:05:19.560 --> 00:05:21.500
but it's the wireless internet that
we give you within our garden."

00:05:21.500 --> 00:05:24.260
And back then there weren't a lot
of applications or services that

00:05:24.310 --> 00:05:27.790
were necessarily enabled or could
be easily converted for application

00:05:27.830 --> 00:05:29.450
and use in the wireless space.

00:05:29.500 --> 00:05:33.220
And probably most importantly,
one of the things that we learned through

00:05:33.220 --> 00:05:36.910
this is it's really important for us to
focus on the environment in which our

00:05:36.910 --> 00:05:38.500
customers are going to use the services.

00:05:38.500 --> 00:05:40.500
It's not really practical to expect that.

00:05:40.510 --> 00:05:43.050
It's not really practical to expect
someone to pick up their phone,

00:05:43.050 --> 00:05:45.500
wait for the connection to happen,
to try to look up a phone number

00:05:45.500 --> 00:05:48.700
when they're competing with voice
minutes and all they have to do is

00:05:48.700 --> 00:05:51.500
dial 411 or call somebody to get the
information that they're looking for.

00:05:51.500 --> 00:05:55.500
So I think one of the most
important takeaways that we had,

00:05:55.500 --> 00:05:58.180
and I think what's important for
folks to understand as they're looking

00:05:58.180 --> 00:06:02.120
at creating more advanced services,
whether they be multimedia

00:06:02.120 --> 00:06:04.820
services or applications,
or any application that they

00:06:04.820 --> 00:06:07.490
think they would like to
bring into the wireless space,

00:06:07.530 --> 00:06:09.500
is that it needs to be relevant
for the mobility of the device.

00:06:09.500 --> 00:06:11.390
And it needs to be relevant for the
mobility scenario and environment

00:06:11.390 --> 00:06:12.380
and be relevant for the time slice.

00:06:12.520 --> 00:06:16.500
Because that's really
what mobility is about.

00:06:16.500 --> 00:06:18.140
It's about I have a few seconds,
I have a time slice of availability

00:06:18.210 --> 00:06:19.520
to be entertained or find
information or connect to

00:06:19.520 --> 00:06:20.500
those that are important to me.

00:06:20.500 --> 00:06:24.490
So I think that's really
what mobility is about.

00:06:24.500 --> 00:06:24.850
It's about I have a few seconds,
I have a time slice of availability

00:06:24.850 --> 00:06:25.140
to be entertained or find
information or connect to

00:06:25.140 --> 00:06:25.500
those that are important to me.

00:06:26.020 --> 00:06:31.870
So we launched M-Mode in early 2002
when we were in the process of rolling

00:06:31.870 --> 00:06:34.900
out our GPRS network nationwide.

00:06:35.040 --> 00:06:38.220
And at that point,
we had hundreds of content providers.

00:06:38.460 --> 00:06:41.900
We had lots of applications,
Java applications, ringtones.

00:06:41.900 --> 00:06:43.880
You could go to 19 different
places and get news.

00:06:43.900 --> 00:06:47.650
And it was like walking into
Walmart and having never been there

00:06:47.760 --> 00:06:50.970
before and just having rows and rows
of aisles of stuff to look for and

00:06:50.970 --> 00:06:52.870
not really knowing how to find it.

00:06:52.900 --> 00:06:56.870
So one of the things that
we did in 2003 was rebuilt a

00:06:56.870 --> 00:06:58.900
whole new M-Mode data service.

00:06:58.900 --> 00:07:04.960
And what was really important here
was we really were trying to focus on,

00:07:04.960 --> 00:07:06.430
again,
the point I made earlier about it being

00:07:06.590 --> 00:07:07.890
relevant to the mobile experience.

00:07:07.900 --> 00:07:11.530
Through some extensive customer
interviews and research and

00:07:11.770 --> 00:07:14.900
working with a leading design
firm here in San Francisco,

00:07:14.900 --> 00:07:19.900
we relaunched M-Mode and we remade it,
and we relaunched it last November.

00:07:19.900 --> 00:07:21.900
And what was really important to
us was that we had a lot of data.

00:07:21.900 --> 00:07:24.900
And what was really important to us was
it needed to appeal to the mass market,

00:07:24.900 --> 00:07:28.860
not to a propellerhead 35-year-old
person like me who was patient enough

00:07:28.900 --> 00:07:31.900
and understood the complexities
of trying to buy a phone,

00:07:31.900 --> 00:07:35.350
figure out how to launch a browser,
get all the settings correct,

00:07:35.350 --> 00:07:36.900
and make it work.

00:07:38.070 --> 00:07:41.260
Because our real goal here
was to drive daily usage.

00:07:41.260 --> 00:07:45.120
We wanted this to be something that was
important and part of people's lives.

00:07:45.200 --> 00:07:48.770
And we wanted it to be a best-in-class
service through work that we were

00:07:48.770 --> 00:07:51.850
doing with our content partners to
make sure it was compelling content

00:07:51.910 --> 00:07:55.780
and it was meaningful and up-to-date.

00:07:56.510 --> 00:08:01.920
So today we have over 260 sites and
applications available through M-mode.

00:08:02.110 --> 00:08:07.930
These range anywhere from repurposed
Internet content or sites that

00:08:07.970 --> 00:08:12.720
have been rewritten or have a
mobile version of their content,

00:08:12.720 --> 00:08:14.870
such as some of the new sites,
Google and others,

00:08:14.870 --> 00:08:19.010
as well as applications for download,
primarily a lot of Java content

00:08:19.070 --> 00:08:20.600
available for phones.

00:08:20.650 --> 00:08:23.210
And additionally,
we even today already have some

00:08:23.210 --> 00:08:28.010
sites that are providing streamed
content on the GPRS network.

00:08:29.770 --> 00:08:32.550
So some of the questions
I get from a lot of people is,

00:08:32.560 --> 00:08:34.090
well,
how does this whole M-mode thing work for

00:08:34.090 --> 00:08:37.080
me as a developer or a content provider,
somebody who wants to create an

00:08:37.100 --> 00:08:39.680
application and bring it to market?

00:08:39.970 --> 00:08:43.170
We at AT&T Wireless,
and through our M-Mode platform,

00:08:43.370 --> 00:08:44.600
we don't host content.

00:08:44.680 --> 00:08:48.790
We don't have big servers in our
data center aggregating lots of

00:08:48.790 --> 00:08:51.890
Java applications for people to
connect to and download and vend them.

00:08:52.200 --> 00:08:55.900
What we do is we follow very
closely the NTT Docomo iMode model,

00:08:55.900 --> 00:08:59.110
where M-Mode is your portal,
your connection to those

00:08:59.390 --> 00:09:03.830
content partners and providers
within our sphere or without.

00:09:03.900 --> 00:09:06.530
We don't prohibit our consumers
or customers from connecting

00:09:06.540 --> 00:09:09.140
anywhere they would like to,
but for those content

00:09:09.190 --> 00:09:13.640
providers that work with us,
they can reach into our entire

00:09:13.640 --> 00:09:17.900
customer base without having to have
an individual billing relationship.

00:09:17.900 --> 00:09:21.420
So it makes it really easy for our
content partners to bring an application

00:09:21.440 --> 00:09:24.900
to market and to be able to monetize
it without having to worry about,

00:09:24.900 --> 00:09:27.210
"I have to print a bill,
I have to figure out how to do all

00:09:27.210 --> 00:09:30.500
these transactions with the customer,"
because we have a very flexible

00:09:30.500 --> 00:09:34.540
mobile commerce platform that we've
put in place to try to... take that

00:09:34.540 --> 00:09:36.900
burden off the content partner.

00:09:36.900 --> 00:09:39.890
So I know you're all probably wondering,
"Well, this is really cool.

00:09:39.890 --> 00:09:44.470
What does this have to do with mobile
video or multimedia or QuickTime?" Well,

00:09:44.470 --> 00:09:46.900
bear with me and I'll get there.

00:09:46.900 --> 00:09:51.310
Because what we are constantly doing is
we're refining our platform and looking

00:09:51.310 --> 00:09:52.900
to deliver new applications and content.

00:09:52.900 --> 00:09:56.810
Some of the examples of new applications
that we've recently launched are

00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:01.900
the mobile traffic applications,
so that in over 70 cities in the country,

00:10:01.900 --> 00:10:03.900
you can pick up your phone
and within a few days,

00:10:03.900 --> 00:10:03.900
you can get your phone back to work.

00:10:03.900 --> 00:10:06.900
And within two clicks,
if you subscribe to the application,

00:10:06.900 --> 00:10:09.890
in your phone,
see the traffic conditions.

00:10:09.910 --> 00:10:14.520
So a logical evolution of this would be,
"Well, it's really nice that I can

00:10:14.530 --> 00:10:17.900
see the traffic conditions,
and I see that there's a backup here,

00:10:17.900 --> 00:10:21.550
but what about that traffic cam
associated with that?" So there's a

00:10:21.550 --> 00:10:25.340
lot of natural extensions that our
multimedia capability and devices

00:10:25.340 --> 00:10:28.900
in the network could enable to
extend applications like that.

00:10:28.900 --> 00:10:31.900
We see the same thing with some of
the other applications with news,

00:10:31.900 --> 00:10:31.900
with games, with movies and movies.

00:10:31.900 --> 00:10:32.900
So we're trying to get that back.

00:10:32.900 --> 00:10:35.860
with movies and movie trailers.

00:10:36.060 --> 00:10:39.250
We are continually working
with our content providers,

00:10:39.370 --> 00:10:43.160
trying to help them understand what
capabilities we have in the devices

00:10:43.160 --> 00:10:47.300
and in the network and our billing
platform to help them bring these

00:10:47.320 --> 00:10:49.880
applications and services to market.

00:10:50.240 --> 00:10:55.100
So we've seen some pretty substantial
success that we're really excited about.

00:10:55.100 --> 00:10:58.100
In 2003, we crossed over the million
subscriber mark for M-Mode.

00:10:58.100 --> 00:11:02.260
These are a million active users,
and we see on average $7 to $8 a

00:11:02.260 --> 00:11:06.100
month of revenue for those users,
in addition to their voice revenue.

00:11:06.100 --> 00:11:09.100
So if you remember back to
that previous slide I put up,

00:11:09.100 --> 00:11:12.100
we're really seeing data revenue
reversing the decline there.

00:11:12.100 --> 00:11:17.020
And we see advanced applications
providing us a tremendous opportunity

00:11:17.100 --> 00:11:22.090
for both ourselves and our developers and
content partners to continue that trend.

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:28.140
So, I talked a little bit
yesterday in Frank's keynote,

00:11:28.140 --> 00:11:31.700
I mentioned 2004 being
the year of convergence,

00:11:31.700 --> 00:11:33.900
some of you may have been there
and heard me make that comment.

00:11:34.200 --> 00:11:38.400
And some of the trends that
I see and that we see at

00:11:38.400 --> 00:11:41.920
AT&T Wireless and with our partners is

00:11:42.180 --> 00:11:47.400
Three key areas that are converging
in this year and in the years to come.

00:11:47.400 --> 00:11:48.990
And some of these
enablers are already here.

00:11:49.090 --> 00:11:52.060
So we launched our
Edge network last year.

00:11:52.200 --> 00:11:53.700
We completed the deployment nationwide.

00:11:53.700 --> 00:11:59.100
So Edge, if you're not familiar,
is an advancement or enhancement to GPRS.

00:11:59.100 --> 00:12:01.860
And GPRS was the data
standard that GSM employs,

00:12:01.860 --> 00:12:05.100
and I'll show a little
network evolution slide there.

00:12:05.100 --> 00:12:10.060
But this allows us to provide customers
with devices that have the capability to

00:12:10.070 --> 00:12:15.550
access data at rates up to 130 kilobits
per second with bursts up to 200.

00:12:15.550 --> 00:12:18.000
So the networks are getting there.

00:12:18.100 --> 00:12:18.970
New devices.

00:12:18.970 --> 00:12:22.400
One of the big challenges to
delivering richer applications

00:12:22.400 --> 00:12:24.100
was device capabilities.

00:12:24.100 --> 00:12:28.430
We had, years ago,
Frank and I mentioned going to Asia and

00:12:28.430 --> 00:12:33.100
seeing demonstrations of mobile
streaming over wireless networks.

00:12:33.100 --> 00:12:35.100
And, you know, one of the big inhibitors
was the Internet.

00:12:35.100 --> 00:12:37.100
And one of the big
challenges was devices.

00:12:37.100 --> 00:12:41.100
We didn't have enough devices that had
the horsepower to stream the video.

00:12:41.100 --> 00:12:45.220
They didn't have the big enough color
displays to actually render it in a

00:12:45.340 --> 00:12:47.090
format that was meaningful to customers.

00:12:47.200 --> 00:12:48.100
And then there was battery life.

00:12:48.100 --> 00:12:51.280
You know, walking around with five
batteries in my pocket so I can,

00:12:51.360 --> 00:12:53.640
you know,
watch 15 minutes of video wasn't

00:12:53.640 --> 00:12:55.530
a really compelling experience.

00:12:56.660 --> 00:12:58.860
And, of course,
new types of applications,

00:12:58.910 --> 00:13:02.850
some of those of which I've showed
you and that we'll take advantage

00:13:02.850 --> 00:13:04.420
of and use this capability.

00:13:04.690 --> 00:13:07.620
But more importantly are the
tools that are needed to bring

00:13:07.620 --> 00:13:09.480
these applications to market.

00:13:09.500 --> 00:13:12.350
Three years ago,
a content partner of ours

00:13:12.390 --> 00:13:16.550
would have been forced to say,
"Okay, I want to deliver rich

00:13:16.580 --> 00:13:18.460
content to my consumers.

00:13:18.590 --> 00:13:21.080
How am I going to do this?" Well,
I could go out and buy a real

00:13:21.080 --> 00:13:23.810
server and pay for lots of
hardware and lots of licenses,

00:13:23.820 --> 00:13:25.430
or should I use packet video?

00:13:25.500 --> 00:13:27.640
But if I use either of those,
then I have to work with the device

00:13:27.640 --> 00:13:30.100
manufacturer to make sure they're
putting the appropriate hardware

00:13:30.110 --> 00:13:32.500
codecs and everything into them.

00:13:32.560 --> 00:13:34.500
And there were a lot of
hodgepodge of standards.

00:13:34.500 --> 00:13:38.800
Standards were evolving and
weren't quite there yet.

00:13:38.970 --> 00:13:42.210
But this year,
I think we've really seen the

00:13:42.340 --> 00:13:46.290
standards turn the corner,
and that we're actually seeing these

00:13:46.360 --> 00:13:49.240
capabilities and standard compliant
capabilities implemented in tools.

00:13:49.240 --> 00:13:51.940
And I think what Apple's done with
QuickTime and their tool set there

00:13:51.940 --> 00:13:55.130
for content authoring and creation
is a perfect example of that.

00:13:55.350 --> 00:13:59.500
It's that easy to create your content,
author it, and deliver it to the device.

00:13:59.980 --> 00:14:01.690
So devices,
there's a whole plethora of devices.

00:14:01.700 --> 00:14:04.500
You walk into any of our
stores or competitor's stores,

00:14:04.500 --> 00:14:07.240
you have a wide variety
of devices to choose from.

00:14:07.260 --> 00:14:10.240
On the consumer side,
from smartphones to camera-enabled

00:14:10.240 --> 00:14:13.310
phones to music-capable
phones to gaming devices,

00:14:13.420 --> 00:14:16.990
some that have been successful
and some not so successful.

00:14:17.010 --> 00:14:20.310
I'm sure some of you have probably
been to that favorite Nokia,

00:14:20.370 --> 00:14:25.120
non-Nokia site, sidetalking.com,
where you see lots of people

00:14:25.140 --> 00:14:27.200
talking on their taco.

00:14:27.280 --> 00:14:30.540
So there's definitely been some
lessons learned by both the operators

00:14:30.550 --> 00:14:31.970
and the device manufacturers.

00:14:32.240 --> 00:14:34.860
On the enterprise side,
we offer a pretty rich array of devices

00:14:35.290 --> 00:14:38.840
to support our enterprise customers'
access to their corporate data,

00:14:38.840 --> 00:14:42.140
applications,
and email in a secure manner,

00:14:42.210 --> 00:14:46.930
both through devices as well as
PC cards and working with various OEMs

00:14:46.930 --> 00:14:52.310
to ensure that the capabilities are
