00:14:53.100 --> 00:14:55.580
The network evolution has been a
really interesting journey for us.

00:14:55.810 --> 00:14:57.600
As I mentioned,
we launched GSM and GPRS and

00:14:57.600 --> 00:15:03.780
completed our build-out in late 2001,
and that completed our GPRS deployment.

00:15:04.210 --> 00:15:06.920
Last year, we did an upgrade nationwide
across all of our network,

00:15:06.920 --> 00:15:10.510
which took us to edge,
which takes us up to 384 kilobits

00:15:10.560 --> 00:15:13.000
per second aggregate throughput.

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:16.000
And again, that varies by conditions
and the device's capability.

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:19.670
Not every edge device is going to
be configured by the manufacturer to

00:15:19.760 --> 00:15:21.930
take advantage of all the throughput.

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:24.730
But on average, the newer devices,
such as the device I'll

00:15:24.740 --> 00:15:27.000
do a little demo on,
the Nokia 6620,

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:29.000
is a four-time slot edge device.

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:32.240
It's a Class 10 device,
for those of you who may be following

00:15:32.240 --> 00:15:34.000
some of the wireless standards.

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:37.740
But what that means is I have the
ability to access data at speeds up to

00:15:37.820 --> 00:15:41.000
about 120 to 130 kilobits per second.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:43.000
That's pretty cool,
considering I'm mobile.

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:44.990
And for the PowerBook users
in the audience,

00:15:45.010 --> 00:15:47.190
this is the greatest
wireless modem I ever had,

00:15:47.190 --> 00:15:51.000
because I just turned
Bluetooth on on my laptop,

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:51.000
and I'm connected.

00:15:51.010 --> 00:15:53.980
It blows dial-up away.

00:15:53.980 --> 00:15:58.450
And now, with improvements we've
made to our network,

00:15:58.450 --> 00:16:01.990
it's accessible just about everywhere.

00:16:02.230 --> 00:16:05.460
We also announced that this year
we would be deploying the next

00:16:05.460 --> 00:16:10.240
evolution on the GSM data path,
and that is our move to wideband CDMA,

00:16:10.240 --> 00:16:13.070
or you may have heard
it referred to as UMTS.

00:16:13.150 --> 00:16:16.100
We'll launch UMTS in
four cities this year.

00:16:16.100 --> 00:16:17.040
We've launched it already.

00:16:17.130 --> 00:16:18.100
It's available in Dallas.

00:16:18.100 --> 00:16:23.100
That was our original launch
city that we were testing in.

00:16:23.100 --> 00:16:25.880
We'll launch it in three
other cities this year.

00:16:26.140 --> 00:16:29.360
And some of you may be familiar
with the fact that we're

00:16:29.360 --> 00:16:31.100
being acquired by Singular.

00:16:31.170 --> 00:16:34.160
And Singular has announced that
they will be--they're fully

00:16:34.160 --> 00:16:37.100
committed to UMTS and will be
launching UMTS nationwide as well.

00:16:37.100 --> 00:16:41.100
So we're really excited that
the bandwidth is increasing,

00:16:41.100 --> 00:16:46.100
and there is a pretty robust
evolution path that takes us to HS.

00:16:46.100 --> 00:16:48.090
That's actually misspelled.

00:16:48.100 --> 00:16:52.090
It should be DPA, and that stands for
High-Speed Data Packet Access.

00:16:52.100 --> 00:16:57.200
But it's just the next evolution
in the GSM/GPRS data path.

00:16:58.550 --> 00:16:59.660
So what is this Edge thing?

00:16:59.660 --> 00:17:02.300
I talked a little bit about it,
but what's great about

00:17:02.300 --> 00:17:04.610
Edge is we rolled out Edge,
and all we had to do was a

00:17:04.660 --> 00:17:06.740
software upgrade to our network.

00:17:06.740 --> 00:17:08.830
We didn't have to go out
and replace radios and roll

00:17:08.850 --> 00:17:10.200
trucks and have forklifts.

00:17:10.200 --> 00:17:14.460
And Edge is essentially just a
new algorithm that takes what was

00:17:14.460 --> 00:17:19.960
previously required three data time
slots in the GPRS world and condenses

00:17:20.010 --> 00:17:24.210
that into one time slot in Edge,
which is really important to

00:17:24.210 --> 00:17:27.120
us because not only it frees
up capacity on the data side,

00:17:27.120 --> 00:17:30.480
it frees up capacity on the voice side,
so it's a big efficiency

00:17:30.490 --> 00:17:31.970
improvement for us.

00:17:33.280 --> 00:17:35.590
So what does this mean to services,
and what does this mean to those

00:17:35.680 --> 00:17:39.190
folks who want to create multimedia
applications and deliver those?

00:17:39.200 --> 00:17:42.150
Well, you can see the evolution here.

00:17:42.230 --> 00:17:43.110
I talked about GPRS.

00:17:43.110 --> 00:17:48.160
We got pretty excited when GPRS came out,
but the reality is, on average,

00:17:48.290 --> 00:17:51.200
a GPRS device supports around
30 kilobits per second,

00:17:51.300 --> 00:17:54.200
which means you probably want
to do a typical video encode at

00:17:54.200 --> 00:17:56.180
around 24 kilobits per second.

00:17:56.200 --> 00:17:59.170
And streaming is probably something a
lot of people would avoid under GPRS,

00:17:59.290 --> 00:18:04.190
unless you were doing some
lower-quality AM quality audio streams.

00:18:04.200 --> 00:18:07.760
But it was good for crude
video or more of a slideshow or

00:18:07.760 --> 00:18:10.170
download and playback scenario.

00:18:10.200 --> 00:18:12.200
With Edge,
we've seen significant improvement,

00:18:12.200 --> 00:18:15.150
and Edge is substantially better
in that we get really good

00:18:15.150 --> 00:18:17.200
quality streaming for video.

00:18:17.200 --> 00:18:22.180
For audio, you can have a pretty
decent experience with AAC,

00:18:22.240 --> 00:18:26.200
the 32K or 64K encodes
on AAC work really well.

00:18:26.200 --> 00:18:31.190
Streamed over Edge,
pretty decent FM quality.

00:18:31.200 --> 00:18:35.200
And the big benefit we get is
the latency is much improved.

00:18:35.200 --> 00:18:39.260
That was one of the biggest complaints
we got from a lot of folks was,

00:18:39.300 --> 00:18:41.200
"That's great, you always have an
always-on GPRS connection,

00:18:41.200 --> 00:18:44.360
but the latency is really
painful." Edge is a substantial

00:18:44.360 --> 00:18:47.210
improvement in latency,
and that's really important

00:18:47.330 --> 00:18:49.200
when it comes to applications.

00:18:49.220 --> 00:18:51.960
And then, moving to UMTS,
we get really excellent

00:18:52.110 --> 00:18:55.200
quality streaming,
even lower latency,

00:18:55.360 --> 00:18:56.200
and a good amount of performance.

00:18:56.200 --> 00:18:59.490
And the typical video encode around
128 kilobits per second provides

00:18:59.490 --> 00:19:01.180
a pretty compelling experience.

00:19:01.200 --> 00:19:04.540
So we're really excited
about the capabilities that

00:19:04.540 --> 00:19:08.510
have converged this year,
and we're excited about our partnership

00:19:08.510 --> 00:19:12.180
with Apple and the work that Apple is
doing to enable folks like yourselves

00:19:12.220 --> 00:19:18.200
to create content and deliver this
content without having to figure out,

00:19:18.200 --> 00:19:20.190
"Am I delivering this to the desktop?

00:19:20.270 --> 00:19:21.180
How do I encode this?

00:19:21.370 --> 00:19:24.450
What are all these standards?"
That's the beauty of

00:19:24.480 --> 00:19:25.200
QuickTime and the authoring tool.

00:19:25.200 --> 00:19:28.300
And the authoring tool is, I just select,
I want to export it,

00:19:28.300 --> 00:19:31.140
and I don't have to be the rocket
scientist to figure this out.

00:19:31.430 --> 00:19:33.170
And it really works.

