like to address or ask is,

00:26:53.690 --> 00:26:54.600
what's so different?

00:26:54.600 --> 00:26:57.590
What's so different about
mobile technologies?

00:26:57.600 --> 00:27:00.550
Well,
I can basically sum it up in two things.

00:27:00.600 --> 00:27:06.600
The first thing is that
it's very personal.

00:27:06.600 --> 00:27:10.220
A mobile phone is the only
device that you have where you

00:27:10.220 --> 00:27:12.600
keep very personal information.

00:27:12.600 --> 00:27:16.580
If any of you have mobile
phones with picture capability,

00:27:16.590 --> 00:27:20.600
a big probability is that you have
your family's picture inside it.

00:27:20.600 --> 00:27:24.600
You have credit card information or
password information as I have it.

00:27:24.630 --> 00:27:27.320
And basically,
this is the only device that

00:27:27.460 --> 00:27:29.600
you keep right up to your face.

00:27:29.600 --> 00:27:31.560
No other device has that capability.

00:27:31.900 --> 00:27:35.600
And that would mean that you could
push content to the mobile phone.

00:27:35.600 --> 00:27:37.590
Anytime, anywhere.

00:27:37.600 --> 00:27:39.600
And, you know,
we always emphasize in Ericsson,

00:27:39.600 --> 00:27:41.600
mobility, mobility, mobility.

00:27:41.600 --> 00:27:46.520
Because that's actually the
key for mobile technologies.

00:27:46.770 --> 00:27:51.550
So, it's the personalization
factor of mobile phones.

00:27:51.600 --> 00:27:58.050
The second part to that is that
users are willing to pay for

00:27:58.050 --> 00:28:01.490
content on the mobile phone.

00:28:01.840 --> 00:28:04.600
This is something that's
very different from internet.

00:28:04.600 --> 00:28:06.510
Or web technologies.

00:28:06.610 --> 00:28:13.380
Because it's very difficult to have
the user perception that the internet

00:28:13.710 --> 00:28:15.520
is a secure way to pay for content.

00:28:15.640 --> 00:28:19.580
Although it's taking
off with Apple's iTunes.

00:28:19.670 --> 00:28:21.600
It's taking off with real networks.

00:28:21.600 --> 00:28:25.550
And a lot of music downloads
we see from the web.

00:28:25.610 --> 00:28:30.540
It's still easier for a user with a
mobile phone to pay for that content.

00:28:30.640 --> 00:28:33.600
So, we see that as a big potential.

00:28:33.600 --> 00:28:37.580
Or a big reason why mobile
networks are so different.

00:28:37.600 --> 00:28:40.600
Just to give you a small example.

00:28:40.600 --> 00:28:43.570
I saw American Idol at home.

00:28:43.600 --> 00:28:47.600
Because my mom comes from, well,
my brother comes from San Francisco.

00:28:47.600 --> 00:28:51.600
And, you know, there's two,
I come from the Philippines as well.

00:28:51.600 --> 00:28:56.590
And there's two contestants there
that have Philippine background.

00:28:56.600 --> 00:29:00.950
And so, when my mom visited me in Sweden,
first thing she said was, "Oh,

00:29:00.950 --> 00:29:03.470
do you know about
American Idol?" And I was like,

00:29:03.580 --> 00:29:06.800
"What's that?" And so,
she starts streaming, you know,

00:29:06.800 --> 00:29:08.590
using our wireless LAN at home.

00:29:08.600 --> 00:29:10.980
She starts streaming, showing me, "Oh,
these are the singers." Now,

00:29:10.980 --> 00:29:14.030
I think she would have done
the same thing if she had

00:29:14.050 --> 00:29:15.450
that capability on her phone.

00:29:15.600 --> 00:29:16.360
You know?

00:29:16.700 --> 00:29:22.600
If I was on the train going,
I think it was four months ago.

00:29:22.600 --> 00:29:25.300
I was going to an office in Atlanta.

00:29:25.690 --> 00:29:28.050
And there was this guy who
was just talking to me about

00:29:28.150 --> 00:29:29.560
Michael Jackson's trial.

00:29:29.600 --> 00:29:31.600
And then his mother called.

00:29:31.600 --> 00:29:33.640
And she said, "Oh,
have you seen the latest information

00:29:33.680 --> 00:29:37.390
about Michael Jackson and what's
happening there?" If she could

00:29:37.390 --> 00:29:42.600
have sent him a link or a telephone
number to call to show her that clip,

00:29:42.610 --> 00:29:44.600
I think she would have, I mean,
he would have, you know,

00:29:44.600 --> 00:29:47.540
shown me that clip and said, "Hey,
here's what's happening

00:29:47.540 --> 00:29:50.350
with Michael Jackson." So,
there's a lot of potential

00:29:50.350 --> 00:29:51.380
for mobile media.

00:29:51.760 --> 00:29:58.540
And 3GPP has seen this potential,
has standardized codecs as well as

00:29:58.850 --> 00:30:00.600
protocols to make sure that streaming
is available on mobile networks.

00:30:00.600 --> 00:30:04.910
I think they're forecasting
roughly $6 billion worth of

00:30:05.030 --> 00:30:07.600
revenue in five years from now.

00:30:07.600 --> 00:30:09.600
So, that's 2008.

00:30:09.770 --> 00:30:15.590
So, that's the first reason why we
think mobile media is successful.

00:30:15.600 --> 00:30:17.590
But there's growth drivers.

00:30:17.600 --> 00:30:22.330
And our colleague from AT&T has already
mentioned that one of the growth drivers

00:30:22.340 --> 00:30:24.410
is the technologies that we have.

00:30:25.100 --> 00:30:25.600
Right?

00:30:25.600 --> 00:30:29.600
And what technologies that we have today
in most of the world is 2G technology.

00:30:29.600 --> 00:30:33.560
Where you have up to 28 kbps.

00:30:33.610 --> 00:30:35.600
Right?

00:30:35.600 --> 00:30:40.670
If you've monitored how Vodafone has
addressed very small numbers of users,

00:30:41.130 --> 00:30:44.000
The first thing I want to say is that
mobile media content on the 2G space,

00:30:44.000 --> 00:30:48.000
since there's very limited bandwidth,
they don't push or they don't provide

00:30:48.000 --> 00:30:51.920
streaming applications as their
thrust or as their core services.

00:30:52.000 --> 00:30:55.960
They're looking at download services
because then you would have the quality

00:30:55.960 --> 00:30:59.990
of the video even though the bit rates
are quite low on these 2G networks.

00:31:00.000 --> 00:31:04.920
But we've seen a lot of the
operators in 2003 move into Edge,

00:31:04.920 --> 00:31:08.960
which have 64 to 144 kbps capabilities.

00:31:09.000 --> 00:31:12.900
One of them is AT&T,
and there's roughly 76 operators

00:31:13.000 --> 00:31:17.890
around the world who have Edge and
have launched Edge in 50 countries.

00:31:18.000 --> 00:31:22.630
So now we have the network
technologies with huge bandwidths

00:31:22.630 --> 00:31:24.990
to deliver mobile content.

00:31:25.000 --> 00:31:30.000
So these are growth drivers
for mobile media services.

00:31:30.000 --> 00:31:35.000
And then there's 3G,
which is 384 kbps with 2 megabits.

00:31:35.230 --> 00:31:37.000
And finally for 3G Evolved, which is HSE.

00:31:37.000 --> 00:31:46.000
As he explained,
it's 384 to 15 megabytes per second.

00:31:46.000 --> 00:31:51.000
I saw a session yesterday
talking about H264.

00:31:51.000 --> 00:31:57.110
That's already been,
or is being introduced in 3GPP and

00:31:57.110 --> 00:32:01.800
there's a lot of hype on that and there's
a lot of activity in making that codec

00:32:01.800 --> 00:32:04.760
available for the wireless handset.

00:32:05.000 --> 00:32:12.000
I think if you have phones that have
not just 64,000 colors available

00:32:12.000 --> 00:32:17.040
but millions and millions of colors,
then you have almost

00:32:17.040 --> 00:32:19.960
DVD quality in 3G networks.

00:32:21.960 --> 00:32:24.460
So, what else do we see?

00:32:24.460 --> 00:32:26.770
We also see,
since there's a lot of bandwidth

00:32:26.890 --> 00:32:31.160
in the operator networks,
we see that the revenue potential for

00:32:31.160 --> 00:32:34.400
mobile data is increasing year by year.

00:32:34.430 --> 00:32:41.750
This figure alone is
from Q2 2002 to Q4 2003.

00:32:41.750 --> 00:32:47.140
And you see 5% increases
in the operator's revenue,

00:32:47.190 --> 00:32:51.910
in the revenue that
they earn off of data.

00:32:52.380 --> 00:32:58.870
And this has moved up from roughly
10% to roughly 30%, and that's

00:32:58.870 --> 00:33:01.770
quite a big number for them.

00:33:02.300 --> 00:33:08.540
Another driver for mobile media is,
as you can see here, is the handsets.

00:33:08.630 --> 00:33:10.140
There are a lot of handsets coming out.

00:33:10.200 --> 00:33:14.330
Last year, when we were trying to sell,
well, two years ago when we were trying

00:33:14.330 --> 00:33:18.200
to sell streaming technologies,
we couldn't find handsets.

00:33:18.200 --> 00:33:23.290
So we had to hire application developers,
create clients, put it in iPacks,

00:33:23.290 --> 00:33:26.120
connect it to a GPRS phone,
and then stream content.

00:33:26.200 --> 00:33:28.050
But that's not the case today.

00:33:28.050 --> 00:33:34.370
You have all the big brands,
all the big terminal manufacturers,

00:33:34.370 --> 00:33:38.580
Sony Ericsson, Nokia, Sanyo, LG,
all these Japanese terminal

00:33:38.580 --> 00:33:41.230
manufacturers,
coming out with phones which

00:33:41.450 --> 00:33:46.200
have video call capabilities,
content streaming capabilities,

00:33:46.320 --> 00:33:49.440
download capabilities,
and this is driving the

00:33:49.440 --> 00:33:51.200
mobile media market as well.

00:33:51.470 --> 00:33:52.080
Okay?

00:33:52.470 --> 00:33:54.420
So...

00:33:55.150 --> 00:34:00.570
Now that we have the handsets,
we have the bandwidth, the next thing is,

00:34:00.570 --> 00:34:03.570
of course,
for operators to take both and offer

00:34:03.570 --> 00:34:06.000
mobile media services to the customers.

00:34:06.250 --> 00:34:09.490
And what we've seen is
there's a... Last year,

00:34:09.500 --> 00:34:11.000
it was more marketing-oriented.

00:34:11.000 --> 00:34:14.990
A lot of operators said, "Okay,
we have streaming capability,"

00:34:15.040 --> 00:34:15.920
but not really fully launched it.

00:34:16.000 --> 00:34:20.000
So it was more a marketing campaign
that they have that capability.

00:34:20.000 --> 00:34:23.000
We're first, and basically,
we have that service up and running.

00:34:23.000 --> 00:34:25.830
But we've seen services
like TV to the mobile,

00:34:25.910 --> 00:34:28.910
video on demand,
video telephony services.

00:34:29.020 --> 00:34:31.000
I'll just give you a short example.

00:34:31.000 --> 00:34:35.210
In Italy and in Sweden,
they have a service

00:34:35.210 --> 00:34:37.910
called Big Brother Live.

00:34:37.910 --> 00:34:41.000
Has anybody heard about Big Brother here?

00:34:41.000 --> 00:34:41.430
No?

00:34:41.500 --> 00:34:43.000
Okay, there.

00:34:43.000 --> 00:34:46.390
Big Brother is a reality TV show,
and basically,

00:34:46.480 --> 00:34:49.620
a group of people stay in one place,
they live there,

00:34:49.630 --> 00:34:50.990
and they have cameras everywhere.

00:34:51.000 --> 00:34:57.230
What they did in Sweden is they
had six live feeds of content,

00:34:57.230 --> 00:35:00.970
plus on-demand content,
and a director's cut, of course.

00:35:01.050 --> 00:35:07.740
The director's cut is the most
important aspect of this whole show.

00:35:08.280 --> 00:35:14.000
And they were able to generate
roughly 50,000 streams per week,

00:35:14.000 --> 00:35:19.000
and these streams were 1 to 2
euro each time you access it.

00:35:19.070 --> 00:35:21.850
So it generated a lot
of money for one show.

00:35:22.200 --> 00:35:25.000
And this is not the only
thing that's picking up.

00:35:25.000 --> 00:35:31.760
We've also seen what we call the
Master Tone Download Service.

00:35:32.250 --> 00:35:34.910
That's been picking up
here as well in the US.

00:35:35.110 --> 00:35:38.870
But it is very popular in Japan,
especially with KDDI.

00:35:39.370 --> 00:35:45.000
They have roughly 7 million
downloads of ringtones per month,

00:35:45.130 --> 00:35:46.990
and each ringtone download is $1 each.

00:35:47.000 --> 00:35:51.000
So that's $7 million every month.

00:35:51.000 --> 00:35:56.000
In the US, Beyonce launched her song
with this Master Tone,

00:35:56.000 --> 00:35:58.000
and you could download the Beyonce song.

00:35:58.140 --> 00:36:05.990
And what it generated
was 1 million downloads.

00:36:06.000 --> 00:36:08.790
So that's roughly $1 million.

00:36:09.000 --> 00:36:13.150
So apart from that,
we have video telephony services,

00:36:13.150 --> 00:36:19.000
where you can call people,
have video-to-video conferences,

00:36:19.000 --> 00:36:23.000
but also you have the
possibility to send numbers,

00:36:23.240 --> 00:36:26.000
and with these numbers, stream content.

00:36:26.000 --> 00:36:32.000
And what advantages that have, of course,
is I could push a special number to you,

00:36:32.000 --> 00:36:38.000
and you would dial up through this
number and access specific content.

00:36:38.480 --> 00:36:41.270
So, what else have we seen?

00:36:41.430 --> 00:36:45.900
As you see,
all the big operators such as Vodafone,

00:36:46.000 --> 00:36:50.090
T-Mobile with their T-Zones,
NT2 Tacoma with their iMode,

00:36:50.250 --> 00:36:56.300
they're all looking at packaging services
and integrating that to the handset.

00:36:56.300 --> 00:37:01.300
It's all about the personalization,
quickness to access that content.

00:37:01.300 --> 00:37:07.300
And in terms of the services that
Ericsson has launched with our operators,

00:37:07.300 --> 00:37:12.300
we've done live TV with a lot
of the Hutchinson companies.

00:37:12.400 --> 00:37:16.210
For infotainment services,
we've done a lot with Telefonica,

00:37:16.460 --> 00:37:18.030
we've done a lot with Amena.

00:37:18.490 --> 00:37:21.240
SmartTone, we have a traffic cam service.

00:37:21.320 --> 00:37:24.200
I think you were talking about
the picture-based traffic cam.

00:37:24.390 --> 00:37:26.300
We have streaming-based
traffic cam services.

00:37:26.300 --> 00:37:29.100
We have streaming-based traffic cam
services in Hong Kong where they have

00:37:29.100 --> 00:37:32.300
certain streets that you can select and
find out what the traffic situation is.

00:37:32.300 --> 00:37:37.010
But of course,
the most mature markets will always be

00:37:37.010 --> 00:37:42.280
Japan and South Korea where they have,
specifically for South Korea,

00:37:42.350 --> 00:37:44.300
they have roughly 400 different channels.

00:37:44.580 --> 00:37:49.150
And they earn roughly 7.5
US dollars per month on top of

00:37:49.470 --> 00:37:55.410
their previous ARPU because of these
streaming and download services.

00:37:57.370 --> 00:38:03.720
So, there is an opportunity and what we
would like to do is have a special

00:38:03.720 --> 00:38:05.960
role in the mobile media space.

00:38:06.110 --> 00:38:06.950
And what is that role?

00:38:07.100 --> 00:38:09.590
First of all,
we address our customers' needs.

00:38:09.640 --> 00:38:11.450
And who is Ericsson's customers?

00:38:11.780 --> 00:38:16.420
It's mainly operators: AT&T, Orange,
Vodafone, T-Mobile.

00:38:16.700 --> 00:38:21.820
These are our customers and what we
provide to them is end-to-end solutions

00:38:22.270 --> 00:38:26.800
for person-to-person services as well
as application-to-person services.

00:38:27.140 --> 00:38:34.360
Person-to-person being SMS, MMS,
video call, instant messaging,

00:38:34.360 --> 00:38:38.800
as well as voice over IP over wireless.

00:38:38.800 --> 00:38:42.280
Apart from that,
we are also trying to bridge

00:38:42.320 --> 00:38:47.110
the gap between the media
industry and the mobile industry.

00:38:47.550 --> 00:38:51.300
Although AT&T is quite advanced
in having a lot of partners,

00:38:51.370 --> 00:38:55.690
a lot of content providers already
having access to the mobile

00:38:55.690 --> 00:38:59.020
network and to the mobile clients,
there are still a lot of

00:38:59.190 --> 00:39:02.050
operators out in the world that
don't have that relationship,

00:39:02.050 --> 00:39:04.800
that don't know what the
content industry is doing.

00:39:05.040 --> 00:39:07.090
They don't know what
your competencies are.

00:39:07.360 --> 00:39:09.600
They think that, "Oh,
maybe it's the same thing as voice

00:39:09.600 --> 00:39:17.200
and I'll just try my luck in this
service." And then they fail.

00:39:17.200 --> 00:39:20.790
So, there's a lot of things that
we would like to do for them.

00:39:20.790 --> 00:39:26.000
And one of the major things that
we would like to do is aggregate

00:39:26.000 --> 00:39:28.800
content and aggregate applications.

00:39:28.900 --> 00:39:31.570
And this is quite important for us.

00:39:31.760 --> 00:39:35.490
And we have an initiative
called Mobility World,

00:39:35.870 --> 00:39:41.520
mainly targeting content developers,
application providers,

00:39:41.630 --> 00:39:47.190
and bringing them in to our portfolio,
testing them, verifying it,

00:39:47.200 --> 00:39:50.390
and then saying, "Alright,
this is a verified application.

00:39:50.420 --> 00:39:53.600
It's a cool service,
and we'd like to take it to market."

00:39:53.770 --> 00:39:55.530
And so that's what we do now.

00:39:55.600 --> 00:39:58.170
We do a matchmaking
and tell the operator,

00:39:58.170 --> 00:40:00.400
"Alright, which one do you want?

00:40:00.400 --> 00:40:01.960
Is it the live traffic cam service?

00:40:01.990 --> 00:40:05.170
Is it the music download
service called EMU's?" This is

00:40:05.170 --> 00:40:06.610
another service we provide.

00:40:06.750 --> 00:40:09.190
And then the operator selects from these.

00:40:09.350 --> 00:40:12.760
And we sell it as part of our portfolio.

00:40:13.640 --> 00:40:15.500
So that's what our role is.

00:40:15.660 --> 00:40:19.640
And again, as I said,
we provide person-to-person

00:40:19.640 --> 00:40:21.490
and application-to-person.

00:40:21.700 --> 00:40:26.240
So what's Ericsson's offering
mainly to our operators?

00:40:26.480 --> 00:40:31.710
We cover handsets from Sony Ericsson,
as well as Ericsson's mobile platforms,

00:40:31.710 --> 00:40:35.500
which is used by six terminal providers.

00:40:35.670 --> 00:40:40.810
We provide access networks,
which is routing, radio-based stations,

00:40:40.810 --> 00:40:42.260
wireless networks.

00:40:42.600 --> 00:40:46.350
We have core networks,
switching infrastructure,

00:40:46.810 --> 00:40:49.500
service networks,
which is basically enablers.

00:40:49.500 --> 00:40:53.330
And we have content and applications
as part of our portfolio.

00:40:53.470 --> 00:40:57.490
And apart from the hardware,
software infrastructure that we sell,

00:40:57.500 --> 00:41:02.500
we provide services to integrate that,
to manage it, and if necessary,

00:41:02.500 --> 00:41:03.500
to host it.

00:41:03.500 --> 00:41:05.500
Because we've won a lot of outsourcing.

00:41:05.500 --> 00:41:10.200
deals when it comes to
supporting wireless networks.

00:41:11.060 --> 00:41:17.610
So, we think that we can take the
next step towards the convergence

00:41:17.650 --> 00:41:22.900
of mobile media and our strength
in the system side from 2G,

00:41:22.900 --> 00:41:27.900
2.5G, and 3G, along with, of course,
Apple, because Apple enables the

00:41:27.900 --> 00:41:29.160
whole end-to-end flow.

00:41:29.160 --> 00:41:32.230
Without the authoring,
without them supporting 3GPP,

00:41:32.330 --> 00:41:33.920
it would be very difficult.

00:41:34.020 --> 00:41:35.760
It would segment the market.

00:41:35.830 --> 00:41:40.160
So, I think that our competencies
in the wireless network with

00:41:40.160 --> 00:41:44.900
Apple's content authoring tools,
the streaming distribution platforms,

00:41:44.990 --> 00:41:50.370
when you tie these things together,
you have a very good story and a

00:41:50.370 --> 00:41:53.840
very good offering for our operators.

00:41:55.200 --> 00:42:00.040
So, I have two more slides,
and basically this one is,

00:42:00.240 --> 00:42:03.240
so now we know that
there's an opportunity.

00:42:03.270 --> 00:42:06.010
We have a specific role that
we've taken as Ericsson,

00:42:06.090 --> 00:42:08.100
and how do we make it successful?

00:42:08.100 --> 00:42:09.310
There's two aspects to it.

00:42:09.310 --> 00:42:13.100
There's the user aspect,
and then there's the operator aspect.

00:42:13.180 --> 00:42:17.020
From the user aspect,
we need to make sure

00:42:17.020 --> 00:42:20.540
that it's easy to use,
it's easy to pay,

00:42:20.570 --> 00:42:22.100
and it's relevant for the user.

00:42:22.100 --> 00:42:25.060
And we have a lot of initiatives
that focus on these three areas.

00:42:25.100 --> 00:42:29.660
From the easy-to-use aspect,
we have an initiative called Zero123,

00:42:29.780 --> 00:42:35.100
which is no manuals, so zero manuals,
one button to access internet services,

00:42:35.100 --> 00:42:39.100
such as, let's say,
a T-zone service or an AT&T service,

00:42:39.100 --> 00:42:43.040
and two seconds to access
the content that I want.

00:42:43.100 --> 00:42:47.060
And three, maximum of three clicks
to find that content.

00:42:47.190 --> 00:42:49.100
So that's Zero123.

00:42:49.410 --> 00:42:54.560
And on the side for relevant services,
how we address that, of course,

00:42:54.560 --> 00:42:58.030
as I said, is we have Mobility World,
where we collect the best

00:42:58.230 --> 00:43:01.100
services around the world,
and we resell this to our operators.

00:43:01.100 --> 00:43:05.910
But apart from that, we do consumer lab,
consumer studies.

00:43:06.090 --> 00:43:09.100
We ask the users,
"What services do you want?"

00:43:09.100 --> 00:43:10.630
Is it a peer-to-peer service?

00:43:10.760 --> 00:43:12.100
Is it an email service?

00:43:12.100 --> 00:43:12.990
Is it a video call service?

00:43:13.100 --> 00:43:15.100
And these are things that we collect.

00:43:15.100 --> 00:43:19.100
And after we collect it,
we create packages around that.

00:43:19.100 --> 00:43:21.100
And then, easy-to-pay.

00:43:21.100 --> 00:43:25.230
This is one of the things that
we really need to consider,

00:43:25.230 --> 00:43:29.590
because at this point in time,
a lot of the operators are missing the

00:43:30.340 --> 00:43:36.840
growth they should be getting because
of the high prices they put on the data.

00:43:37.100 --> 00:43:41.100
I think it's averaging
roughly $20 to $30.

00:43:41.100 --> 00:43:43.100
Right.

00:43:43.100 --> 00:43:45.100
Per megabyte of data.

00:43:45.100 --> 00:43:47.230
So we need to make sure
that the packages are there,

