01:02:01.740 --> 01:02:05.710
it's user-created content that's
going to make this market take off,

01:02:05.710 --> 01:02:09.800
and not necessarily just
professionally created content.

01:02:09.800 --> 01:02:13.160
At some point, I think we're going to see
the same phenomena we've seen,

01:02:13.300 --> 01:02:17.000
where people use a service a lot,
for like the first year,

01:02:17.000 --> 01:02:17.910
and then there's a drop-off.

01:02:18.000 --> 01:02:21.480
I think what's truly going to
have the stickiness is when

01:02:22.050 --> 01:02:26.000
users can integrate their own
content with professional content,

01:02:26.000 --> 01:02:30.810
or just create their own
content and be able to use it

01:02:30.870 --> 01:02:33.570
and display it on their phone.

01:02:34.050 --> 01:02:36.530
Of course,
that also means that there needs to be

01:02:36.580 --> 01:02:38.970
some developments in the metadata field.

01:02:39.000 --> 01:02:44.960
In fact, being able to capture
in real time metadata.

01:02:44.960 --> 01:02:48.960
That's going to be one of the source
of innovations in the years to come,

01:02:48.980 --> 01:02:53.180
as will your indexing
strategies of that metadata,

01:02:53.180 --> 01:02:57.960
and how you correlate it
with user preferences.

01:02:58.270 --> 01:03:00.520
In order to be able to
push the right things,

01:03:00.520 --> 01:03:07.640
in order to be able to make sure
you can recommend to the client,

01:03:07.640 --> 01:03:10.280
you know, well, if you like this song,
you might like this song,

01:03:10.280 --> 01:03:15.150
and you can download it right
now or hear a sample right now.

01:03:15.430 --> 01:03:20.000
And finally, I think we're positioned to
provide innovative services.

01:03:20.000 --> 01:03:24.240
That sounds probably banal,
but I think the reason I put

01:03:24.360 --> 01:03:28.890
that up there because of the,
I think it's going to be important

01:03:28.890 --> 01:03:32.980
to all carriers to treat their
clients in a holistic manner,

01:03:32.980 --> 01:03:38.420
not as a wireless client sometimes and
sometimes as a different type of client.

01:03:38.420 --> 01:03:41.540
They're one client with
different contexts.

01:03:41.540 --> 01:03:45.880
In different contexts,
they have access to different devices.

01:03:46.010 --> 01:03:50.240
And by understanding
what their contexts are,

01:03:50.280 --> 01:03:53.570
you're in a better position
to be able to provide them the

01:03:53.740 --> 01:03:55.580
content that they may need.

01:03:55.680 --> 01:03:57.370
All right, thank you.

01:03:57.810 --> 01:04:00.670
Kevin, thank you very much.